Theoretical Framework

stfgov - How satisfied with the national government

trstprl - Trust in country’s parliament eduyrs - Years of full-time education completed stfeco - How satisfied with present state of economy in country stfdem - How satisfied with the way democracy works in country gndr - Gender

Most developed countries in the world are democracies, and since the last century democratic countries especially in Europe became the subject of interest for many sociologists and political scientists. Scholars began to be very interested in people well-being, how democracy works, how much people trust in government and whether they are satisfied with its work etc. Recently many research has been conducted about the origins of people’s trust in their governments, what are the factors that influence on their satisfaction with the policy directions of their governments. One of the articles by Chanley, Virginia A. (2000) defined several factors that have an impact on public opinion and perception of the governments’ work, for example people’s sustainability of economy expectations and satisfaction with governmental institutions, like parliament. Another scientist, Mark E Warren (1999) had an assumption that subjective well-being of a person leads to the support of democratic institutions and then the satisfaction with the way how democracy works in the country appears as the predictor of satisfaction with the government and all other political institutions. Moreover, gender also have some influence, according to Hansen, Michael A.; Goenaga, Agustín (2019), for women the satisfaction with democracy is more likely to lead to the satisfaction with the national government. That is so, as women tend to prioritize different aspects of democracy. Recent studies by Monika L. McDermott; David R. Jones; (2020) also showed that there is a direct connection between gender and satisfaction and support of government. The study concluded that females and all in all femininity are more likely to be satisfied with the work of national government especially if the ruling party is right-wing, however both genders are equally satisfied with the government if the ruling party is left-wing. Moreover, Norris (1999) indicated that people with higher education have less trust in government since they look more criticized towards governments.

For our dependent variable (stfgov) we take people’s opinions on how they are satisfied with the national government. This is the subject of our interest, it shows how much people are satisfied with their life, how they evaluate the work of their government etc. The independent variable (trstprl) shows how much people trust the parliament of the country, we suppose that trust in every political institution represents and constitute the trust to the whole political system. The same logic relates to the independent variables (stfeco) which shows how satisfied with present state of economy in country and (stfdem) which shows how satisfied with the way democracy works in country. These variables are about personal well-being, whether they think that their democratic rights are protected by the government and that the government is wealthy enough to provide people public goods, high wages, and high standards of living. The other variable is (eduyrs) show number of years of full-time education completed. It is expected that people who are highly educated have less level of trust and satisfaction of the government as they would have more critical view on its deeds. The last variable is (gndr) gender, to track what sex is more likely to be satisfied with the national government.

All in all, the aim of or research is to analyze opinions on political system of the European Union citizens, as we can consider the EU as homogeneous region with similar political institutes and values. We want to track the level of satisfaction of the national governments, what factors influence it and whether there are positive correlations between trust to political institutions, state of economy, democracy, and negative correlation with number of years of education.

References - Chanley, Virginia A.; Rudolph, Thomas J.; Rahn, Wendy M. (2000). The Origins and Consequences of Public Trust in Government. Public Opinion Quarterly, 64(3), 239–256. - Democracy and Trust. Edited by Mark E. Warren. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1999. - Hansen, Michael A.; Goenaga, Agustín (2019). Gender and Democratic Attitudes: Do Women and Men Prioritize Different Democratic Institutions?. Politics & Gender - Monika L. McDermott;David R. Jones; (2020). Gender, Sex, and Trust in Government . Politics & Gender - Norris, P. (1999) Critical Citizens: Global Support for Democratic Government. OUP, Oxford.

Variables Manipulations

Before creating a model, we need to recode variables.

data$stfgov <- car::recode(data$stfgov,"c(0) = '0'; c(1) = '0'; c(2) = '0'; c(3) = '0'; c(4) = '0'; c(5) = '1'; c(6) = '1'; c(7) = '1'; c(8) = '1'; c(9) = '1'; c(10) = '1'")


data$stfgov <- car::recode(data$stfgov,"c(0) = 'Dont_Satisf'; c(1) = 'Satisf'") 

data = data %>%
  mutate(stfgov = factor(stfgov, levels = c("Dont_Satisf", "Satisf")))

data$gndr <- car::recode(data$gndr,"c(1) = 'Male'; c(2) = 'Female'") 

data = data %>%
  mutate(gndr = factor(gndr, levels = c("Male", "Female")))

Logit model

model1 <- glm(stfgov~stfdem*gndr+stfeco+trstprl+gndr+eduyrs, family = binomial(link = logit), data = data)

Interpretation of the model

All the variables are significant. -The intercept equals -3.5 that is the expected value of the dependent variable, when all the independent variables equal 0 -stfdem: the log of odds ratio of being satisfied with the government increases by 0.35 with each additional score on satisfaction with democracy. Therefore, people who are more satisfied with state’s democracy are more likely to be satisfied with government -stfeco: the log of odds ratio of being satisfied with the government increases by 0.29 with each additional score on satisfaction with state’s economy. Therefore, people who are more satisfied with state’s economy are more likely to be satisfied with government -trstprl: the log of odds ratio of being satisfied with the government increases by 0.23 with each additional score on trusting country’s Parliament. Therefore, people who are more satisfied with state’s Parliament are more likely to be satisfied with government -gndr (Female): For females the log of odds ratio of being satisfied with the government is lower by 0.19 compared to males. Therefore, females are less likely to be satisfied with the government -eduyrs: the log of odds ratio of being satisfied with the government decreases by 0.07 with each year of education. Therefore, more educated people are less likely to be satisfied with government

Interaction effect stfdem:gndrFemale: the log of odds ratio of being satisfied with the government increases by 0.07 with the growth of satisfaction with democracy for females

Odds ratio

exp(coef(model1))
##       (Intercept)            stfdem        gndrFemale            stfeco 
##        0.03033846        1.42448963        0.82827557        1.33911174 
##           trstprl            eduyrs stfdem:gndrFemale 
##        1.25419800        0.93647816        1.05919196

Interpretation:

stfdem: the odds of satisfaction with government increase by 43% with the growth of satisfaction with democracy (odds - 1) stfeco: the odds of satisfaction with government increase by 34% with each point on satisfaction with economy scale (odds - 1) trstprl: the odds of satisfaction with government increase by 25% with the growth of trust to the parliament (odds - 1) eduyrs: the odds of satisfaction with government decrease by 6% with each year of education (1-odds) gndr: the odds of satisfaction with government are 0.27 lower for females compared to males

stfdem/gndrFemale: for female gender each increase of satisfaction with demography rise odds ratio of governmental satisfaction by 6% (odds - 1)

plot(model1)

### Interpreting the model fit

Multicollinearity <2 is good

car::vif(model1)
##      stfdem        gndr      stfeco     trstprl      eduyrs stfdem:gndr 
##    2.160315    8.382263    1.165886    1.155074    1.058047    9.146954

We may see that there is no multicollinearity between variables, since test score is <2.2 for all variables. The only exception are “Gender” and “stfdem:gndr”, bit it is OK since there is interaction effect.

PseudoR2(model1)

Interpretation of the model

All the variables are significant. -The intercept equals -2 that is the expected value of the dependent variable, when all the independent variables equal 0 -stfdem: with each additional score on satisfaction with state’s democracy z-score of probability of being satisfied with the government increases by 0.2. Therefore, people who are more satisfied with state’s democracy are more likely to be satisfied with government -gndrFemale: for females z-score of probability of being satisfied with government is lower by 0.10 compared to males. Therefore, females are less likely to be satisfied with government. - stfeco: with each additional score on satisfaction with state’s economy z-score of probability of being satisfied with the government increases by 0.17. Therefore, people who are more satisfied with state’s economy are more likely to be satisfied with government -trstprl: with each additional score on trusting state’s Parlament z-score of probability of being satisfied with the government increases by 0.13. Therefore, people who are more trustful to state’s Parlament are more likely to be satisfied with the government -eduyrs: with each additional year of education z-score of probability of being satisfied with the government decreases by 0.04. Therefore, more educated people are less likely to be satisfied with government

Interaction effect: stfdem:gndrFemale: z-score of probability of being satisfied with the government increases by 0.03 with the growth of satisfaction with democracy for females

All in all, all the coefficients became smaller in the probit model.

Average marginal effect shows that:

On average the probability of satisfaction with government others decreases by 0.02 with each year of education

On average for females the probability is higher by 0.02
On average the probability of satisfaction with government by the person increases with the growth of democracy satisfaction by 0.06
On average the probability of satisfaction with government by the person increases with the growth of satisfaction with economy as well by 0.04
On average for those who trust the parliament more the probability of satisfaction with government others rises by 0.03

To conclude, we may state that theory has been approved by the models. Our analysis has shown that females’ satisfaction with democracy has more influence on the satisfaction with government, than for males. We also observed, that satisfaction with economy and trust to the country’s Parliament has positive impact on the government satisfaction. In contrast, education negatively correlates with government satisfaction. Despite, some tests were not perfect, all results are statistically significant. Thus, we may observe which factors may influence satisfaction with government among European countries.
